<div class="mb-requirement-container">
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15455">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> </span>
      <b>NOTE: </b> The official merit badge pamphlets are now free and
      downloadable
      <a
        href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Pamphlets/Radio.pdf"
        target="_blank"
        >HERE</a
      >
      or can be purchased at the
      <a href="https://www.scoutshop.org/" target="_blank ">Scout Shop.</a>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15456">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 1. </span>
      <b>Radio Safety.</b> Explain the safety precautions for working with radio
      gear, including:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15456 mb-requirement-id-15457">
        (a) Grounding for direct and alternating current circuits, power
        outlets, antennas, and lightning. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/JBpQ9Fodz_Q" target="_blank"
          >Grounding Explained (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/zLW_7TPf310" target="_blank"
          >What Is Ground? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15456 mb-requirement-id-15458">
        (b) Preventing and treating electrical burns <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://burncenters.com/burns/burn-services/electrical-burns/"
          target="_blank"
          >First Aid for Electrical Burns (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/O2VpgB8Xrzs" target="_blank"
          >Rescue and First Aid for Electric Shock (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15456 mb-requirement-id-15459">
        (c) Preventing lithium-ion battery fires in cell phones and other
        devices. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/7OiHAPmv75A" target="_blank"
          >Preventing Lithium Ion Battery Fires (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15461">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 2. </span>
      <b>Radio Fundamentals.</b> Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15461 mb-requirement-id-15462">
        (a) Do the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15462 mb-requirement-id-15532">
        (1) Draw a chart of the electromagnetic spectrum covering 300 kilohertz
        (kHz) to 3,000 megahertz (MHz). <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/JatvwodZZRY" target="_blank"
          >Frequency Bands (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15462 mb-requirement-id-15533">
        (2) Label the MF, HF, VHF, UHF, and microwave portions of the spectrum
        on your diagram. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://terasense.com/terahertz-technology/radio-frequency-bands/"
          target="_blank"
          >Radio Frequency Bands (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15462 mb-requirement-id-15534">
        (3) Locate on your chart at least eight radio services, such as AM and
        FM commercial broadcast, citizens band (CB), television, amateur radio
        (at least four amateur radio bands), public service (police and fire),
        cellular, Wi-Fi, and Bluetooth. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://strykerradios.com/ham-radios/ham-radio-frequencies-common-uses-you-should-know/"
          target="_blank"
          >Common Uses of Ham Radio Frequencies (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15461 mb-requirement-id-15464">
        (b) Discuss the following topics with your counselor:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15464 mb-requirement-id-15506">
        (1) The definition of radio <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/bdAxVp5HWis" target="_blank"
          >Communication and Radio (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/mp6St2hgv8A" target="_blank"
          >What Is a Radio Wave? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15464 mb-requirement-id-15507">
        (2) The differences between broadcast radio and two-way radio <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/CU8cVH8YYuo" target="_blank"
          >How Broadcast Radio Works (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/iEKrp8at6i8" target="_blank"
          >Two-Way Radios Explained: VHF vs UHF, FCC Licenses, and More FAQs
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15464 mb-requirement-id-15508">
        (3) The differences between commercial broadcast radio and hobby radio
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Xt3RVtfnbPA" target="_blank"
          >What Is Ham Radio? How Amateur Radio Works (No Internet Required)
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15466">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 3. </span>
      <b>How Radio Waves Travel.</b> Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15466 mb-requirement-id-15467">
        (a) Sketch a diagram showing how different radio wavelengths can travel
        locally or around the world. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/tVAVPpxdg9k" target="_blank"
          >What Is Propagation? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/61UqLXVJM7s" target="_blank"
          >Why Some AM Radio Stations Don't Work at Night (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15466 mb-requirement-id-15468">
        (b) Explain how the radio stations WWV and WWVH can be used to help
        determine what you can expect to hear when you listen to a shortwave
        radio. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/yB2A_ANhH_k" target="_blank"
          >WWV WWVH Time Signals (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15466 mb-requirement-id-15469">
        (c) Explain the difference between a distant (DX) and a local station.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/VKb9eMZKcSE" target="_blank"
          >DXing: D for Distance, X for Unknown (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/KZrhjfKY-9g" target="_blank"
          >Ham Radio DX Fun (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15502">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 4. </span>
      <b>Information by Radio.</b> Discuss the following with your counselor:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15502 mb-requirement-id-15535">
        (a) How radio waves carry information using continuous wave (CW) Morse
        Code transmission, amplitude modulation (AM), frequency modulation (FM),
        single sideband (SSB) transmission, and frequency hopping. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/drLxfjqZHVo" target="_blank"
          >Radio Wave Modulation (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/shorts/Dr5Sai2IVuE" target="_blank"
          >Frequency Hopping (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/shorts/GA3vr55ZwmU" target="_blank"
          >Frequency Hopping and WiFi (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15502 mb-requirement-id-15536">
        (b) How digitized radio standards including Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, and 5G can
        offer more reliable data transmission and reception than analog
        standards. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/btgAUdbj85E" target="_blank"
          >Analog vs Digital Data (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/ZWdT-6Ld71Q" target="_blank"
          >Digital vs Analog. What's the Difference? Why Does It Matter?
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Yl5ezrw7T1c" target="_blank"
          >Analog vs Digital Radio: A Beginner's Guide to Radio Modes (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15502 mb-requirement-id-15537">
        (c) How the effective range varies for different methods of information
        encoding. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/8XC2hv1Tfpc" target="_blank"
          >Relationship Between Frequency, Data Rate, and Distance (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/whEqaxlCVSs" target="_blank"
          >How Radio Waves Transmit Information (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15502 mb-requirement-id-15538">
        (d) How the maximum data rate from a Wi-Fi radio system compares to a
        hard-wired or fiber-optic system. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/mLS9XXiPNcE" target="_blank"
          >Ethernet vs WiFi, Which One Is Faster？ (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtube.com/shorts/hlLYg2FUFq8" target="_blank"
          >Shattering Limits: 402 Terabits per Second (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15470">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 5. </span>
      <b>Radio Hardware and Services.</b> Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15470 mb-requirement-id-15471">
        (a) Explain the differences between a block diagram and a schematic
        diagram. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/_HZ-EQ8Hc8E" target="_blank"
          >How To Read a Schematic (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15470 mb-requirement-id-15472">
        (b) Draw a block diagram for a radio station that shows a microphone,
        speaker, transceiver, transmitter, receiver, amplifier, feedline, and
        antenna and discuss the function of these components.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15470 mb-requirement-id-15473">
        (c) List consumer devices and services that use analog or digital radio
        communications. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Yl5ezrw7T1c" target="_blank"
          >Analog vs Digital Radio: A Beginner's Guide to Radio Modes (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15470 mb-requirement-id-15474">
        (d) Explain how NOAA Weather Radio (NWR) can alert you to danger.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/bWcU_IPnXgY" target="_blank"
          >National Weather Service: Weather Warning Process (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/ZqmguEWojYw" target="_blank"
          >Ways To Get Warnings (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15470 mb-requirement-id-15475">
        (e) Explain how RFID works and what are some of its uses in everyday
        life. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/qRimFDF7FR0" target="_blank"
          >What Is RFID Technology? And How It Works? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/ziDlycAZb9I" target="_blank"
          >What is RFID (Radio Frequency Identification)? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15503">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 6. </span>
      <b>Radio Regulation.</b> Discuss the following with your counselor:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15503 mb-requirement-id-15539">
        (a) What the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) does and how it is
        different from the International Telecommunication Union (ITU). <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/KiSLp7h5Qeo" target="_blank"
          >What Is the FCC? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15503 mb-requirement-id-15540">
        (b) How radio station call signs are used in broadcast radio and amateur
        radio. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/1ES-I3q-odY" target="_blank"
          >Ham Radio Call Signs (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/R_GvgmeRADo" target="_blank"
          >Ham 101 Episode 7: Your Call Sign (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/kcAROYxzJ4U" target="_blank"
          >Broadcast Call Signs Explained (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/vZgWdZImg9Q" target="_blank"
          >When To ID With Your Call Sign (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15503 mb-requirement-id-15541">
        (c) How the phonetic alphabet is used to communicate clearly. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/cFhZLaLDILQ" target="_blank"
          >Learn the Phonetic Alphabet (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15504">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 7. </span>
      <b>Cell Phones</b> Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15504 mb-requirement-id-15542">
        (a) Explain how cellular systems differ from broadcast and hobby radio.
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/1JZG9x_VOwA" target="_blank"
          >How Your Mobile Phone Works (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15504 mb-requirement-id-15543">
        (b) Explain what Airplane Mode is and why it is important. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/841MdLwynXg" target="_blank"
          >What Really Happens When You Turn On Airplane Mode (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/iKYHf22qVdM" target="_blank"
          >What Happens if You Don't Put Your Phone in Airplane Mode? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15504 mb-requirement-id-15544">
        (c) Explain how cell phones keep the correct time and show locations and
        elevations. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/wCcARVbL_Dk" target="_blank"
          >How GPS Works Today (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/8eTlI19_57g" target="_blank"
          >GPS, How Does It Work? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15504 mb-requirement-id-15545">
        (d) Explain the benefits and limitations of cell phones in emergencies.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/RAa5GHcIki4" target="_blank"
          >How Reliable Are Cell Phones in an Emergency? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/6-9HUBO2HeY" target="_blank"
          >When Cell Phones Fail: Staying Connected When It Matters Most
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Dx1Wn7JpObM" target="_blank"
          >We Tested the iPhone 14's Emergency SOS via Satellite (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.abc10.com/article/news/local/crash-detection-feature-heres-where-you-can-find-it/103-525d6812-ce6b-4dad-b888-1f5fd490493d"
          target="_blank"
          >Does Your Phone Have a Crash Detection Feature? (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15504 mb-requirement-id-15546">
        (e) Explain wireless charging for cell phones and other devices.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/CvXJes3BREM" target="_blank"
          >How Do Wireless Phone Chargers Work? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/NjeUxwGblm8" target="_blank"
          >How Your Phone Charges Through Thin Air (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15476">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 8. </span>
      <b>Amateur and Professional Radio.</b> Do ONE of the following options:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15476 mb-requirement-id-15477">
        <b>Option A—Amateur Radio.</b> Do ALL of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15477 mb-requirement-id-15478">
        (1) Tell why the FCC has an amateur radio service. Describe activities
        that amateur radio operators can do on the air, once they have earned an
        amateur radio license. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/zWoZ_mqjInA" target="_blank"
          >Why Do They Call It Ham Radio? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/BCSZH7UzOxg" target="_blank"
          >Episode 3: How To Get a Ham Radio License | Bcu Freshman Class
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15477 mb-requirement-id-15479">
        (2) Explain differences between the Technician, General, and Extra Class
        license requirements and privileges. Explain who administers amateur
        radio exams. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://www.arrl.org/getting-licensed" target="_blank"
          >Ham Radio License Levels (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15477 mb-requirement-id-15480">
        (3) Explain at least five Q signals or amateur radio terms. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/JFdfPSPrwE4" target="_blank"
          >Q-Codes, Logs, and QRZ.com (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/580VdJlXZ_A" target="_blank"
          >Q-Codes and Calling CQ (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15477 mb-requirement-id-15481">
        (4) Explain how you would make an emergency call on voice or Morse code.
        <br />Resources:
        <a href="https://youtu.be/9pHZR_aiTPU" target="_blank"
          >How To Use Your VHF Marine Radio To Call for Help in a Boat Emergency
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/33JSFzFB8U8" target="_blank"
          >Ham Radio Disaster Messaging Demo (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/MaRLuoJRwFg" target="_blank"
          >Using Ham Radio To Call for Help in an Emergency—What You Should Do!
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15477 mb-requirement-id-15482">
        (5) Explain the differences between handheld, mobile, and base station
        transceivers and their uses. Explain the use of amateur radio repeaters.
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/BH19eKBuKwY" target="_blank"
          >How Do Repeaters Work? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15477 mb-requirement-id-15483">
        (6) Using proper call signs, Q signals, and abbreviations, carry on a
        10-minute real or simulated amateur radio contact using voice, Morse
        code, or digital mode. Properly log the real or simulated amateur radio
        contact, and record the signal report. <br /><b>Note: </b>Licensed
        amateur radio operators may substitute five QSL cards as evidence of
        contacts with five amateur radio operators.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15476 mb-requirement-id-15484">
        <b>Option B—Radio Broadcasting.</b> Do ALL of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15484 mb-requirement-id-15485">
        (1) Discuss with your counselor FCC broadcast regulations. Include power
        levels, frequencies, and the regulations for low-power stations.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/DioqjwYzJiA" target="_blank"
          >How To Start a FM Radio Station! (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/9_gFYKGMO5Y" target="_blank"
          >In Historic Victory for Community Radio, FCC Puts 1,000 Low-Power FM
          Frequencies Up for Grabs (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15484 mb-requirement-id-15486">
        (2) Prepare a program schedule for radio station "KBSA" of exactly
        one-half hour, including music, news, commercials, and proper station
        identification. Record your program on audiotape or in a digital audio
        format, using proper techniques. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/oOFdg9roook" target="_blank"
          >Build the Best Programming for Your Radio Station! (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15484 mb-requirement-id-15487">
        (3) Listen to and properly log 15 broadcast stations. Determine the
        program format and target audience for five of these stations. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtube.com/shorts/SoCL56dEy_k" target="_blank"
          >Radio Stations Over The World (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15484 mb-requirement-id-15488">
        (4) Explain to your counselor at least eight terms used in commercial
        broadcasting, such as segue, cut, fade, continuity, remote, Emergency
        Alert System, network, cue, dead air, PSA, and playlist. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://www.radioconnection.com/glossary/" target="_blank"
          >Radio Broadcasting Glossary (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15484 mb-requirement-id-15489">
        (5) Discuss with your counselor alternative radio platforms such as
        internet streaming, satellite radio, and podcasts. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/HzYX0LQgt-k" target="_blank"
          >Shortwave Radio Top Ten Tips for Beginners Listen to Online Receivers
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15476 mb-requirement-id-15490">
        <b>Option C—Shortwave and Medium-Wave Listening.</b> Do ALL of the
        following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15490 mb-requirement-id-15491">
        (1) Listen across several shortwave bands for four one-hour periods-at
        least one period during daylight hours and at least one period at night.
        Log the stations properly and locate them geographically on a map,
        globe, or web-based mapping service. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtube.com/shorts/GuGMFXdco_4" target="_blank"
          >Unlock Shortwave Listening: Fun With HF Ham Radios (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/dIeK-3PlL9U" target="_blank"
          >Incredible Shortwave Radio Stations Listing (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15490 mb-requirement-id-15492">
        (2) Listen to several medium-wave stations for two one-hour periods, one
        period during daylight hours and one period at night. Log the stations
        properly and locate them on a map, globe, or web-based mapping service.
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/KIBRDcNnIk4" target="_blank"
          >Great Mediumwave AM radio DXers resource for Finding Stations MWLIST
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15490 mb-requirement-id-15493">
        (3) Compare your daytime and nighttime logs; note the frequencies on
        which your selected stations were loudest during each session. Explain
        differences in the signal strength from one period to the next. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/UL4ZrttSNv4" target="_blank"
          >Shortwave for Beginners Day and Night Differences in Radio
          Propagation of Signals (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/X-Vnpsi46XE" target="_blank"
          >Understanding Daytime and Night Time Patterns To Increase Shortwave
          Listening Pleasure (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/byvMpUt7k58" target="_blank"
          >Shortwave Propagation 101 Part 1 Daytime and Nighttime Propagation
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15490 mb-requirement-id-15494">
        (4) Compare your medium-wave broadcast station logs and explain why some
        distant stations are heard at your location only during the night.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/_VDUGiJhK78" target="_blank"
          >Why AM Radio Signals Propogate Farther At Night Than During the Day
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/jpbkcakEvWs" target="_blank"
          >Ground Wave Propagation / Types of Radio Waves (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15490 mb-requirement-id-15495">
        (5) Demonstrate listening to a radio broadcast using a smartphone/cell
        phone. Include international broadcasts in your demonstration. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/EUXYo9vS30w" target="_blank"
          >How To Listen to FM Radio on Android or iPhone! (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/K9LbIu4p1fc" target="_blank"
          >Unlock the Hidden FM Radio in Your Android Smart Phone (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15476 mb-requirement-id-15496">
        <b>Option D—Amateur Radio Direction Finding.</b> Do ALL of the
        following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15496 mb-requirement-id-15497">
        (1) Describe amateur radio direction finding and explain why direction
        finding is important as both an activity and in competition. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/1Qseg0mWpcI" target="_blank"
          >Amateur Radio Foxhunting: Equipment, Techniques, &amp; Getting
          Started—Ham Radio Transmitter Hunting (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/bWs6shlc9m0" target="_blank"
          >Radio Direction Finding: AKA How "They" Can Find You (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15496 mb-requirement-id-15498">
        (2) Describe what frequencies and equipment are used for ARDF or fox
        hunting. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/HQxGJDvRnPU" target="_blank"
          >Ham Radio Fox Hunting 101 (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15496 mb-requirement-id-15499">
        (3) Build a simple directional antenna for either of the two frequencies
        used in ARDF. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/KihdX-8XKIE" target="_blank"
          >Two Simple Ham Radio Antennas You Can Use for Fox Hunting (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15496 mb-requirement-id-15500">
        (4) Participate in a simple fox hunt using your antenna along with a
        provided receiver. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtube.com/shorts/i2x_t08KUw8" target="_blank"
          >Ham Radio Fox Hunt? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15496 mb-requirement-id-15501">
        (5) Show, on a map, how you located the "fox" using your receiver.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15476 mb-requirement-id-15547">
        <b
          >Option E—Family Radio Service (FRS) and General Mobile Radio Service
          (GMRS) Walkie Talkies. </b
        >Do ALL of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15547 mb-requirement-id-15548">
        (1) Explain what the Family Radio Service (FRS) and General Mobile Radio
        Service (GMRS) are and how they are different from each other, from
        other commercial two-way radios, and from Citizens Band (CB) and amateur
        radio (ham). <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/cuqPawftFhQ" target="_blank"
          >FRS VS GMRS: A Radio Service Comparison Guide (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15547 mb-requirement-id-15549">
        (2) Explain each of the following for using a FRS radio or GMRS walkie
        talkie:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15549 mb-requirement-id-15550">
        (a) Is any type of license needed to use these radios? If so: what kind?
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtube.com/shorts/8HUTrWX_A_k" target="_blank"
          >Walkie Talkies—FRS vs GMRS vs Ham (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15549 mb-requirement-id-15551">
        (b) What radio frequencies are used and how is information encoded?
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://www.tiktok.com/@onthetrailradio/video/7319691451955154222"
          target="_blank"
          >Troubleshooting Radio Connections (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15549 mb-requirement-id-15552">
        (c) How much power can be used when transmitting? <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://www.tiktok.com/@onthetrailradio/video/7490642330546916638"
          target="_blank"
          >FRS vs. GMRS (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15549 mb-requirement-id-15553">
        (d) What type of antenna can be used? <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtube.com/shorts/wHJCA43UK8Y" target="_blank"
          >Differences between GMRS and FRS (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15549 mb-requirement-id-15554">
        (e) What is the effective range and what limits it?
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15549 mb-requirement-id-15555">
        (f) What are common everyday uses for these radios?
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15549 mb-requirement-id-15556">
        (g) How can these radios be useful in an emergency? <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zy5lNBGoORw" target="_blank"
          >HAM and GMRS Radios for Emergencies (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xT-2IVItSZY" target="_blank"
          >FRS and GMRS Radio for Emergency Communications (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.radiodesigngroup.com/blog/the-vital-role-of-ham-radio-in-disaster-preparedness"
          target="_blank"
          >The Vital Role of Ham Radio in Disaster Preparedness (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15547 mb-requirement-id-15557">
        (3) Use the FRS radios or GMRS walkie talkies with family, friends, or
        Scouts on a hike, at an event, or in a team game. Discuss what you
        learned with your counselor.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15558">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 9. </span>
      <b>Careers.</b> Do ONE of the following.
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15558 mb-requirement-id-15559">
        (a) Explore careers related to radio. Research one career to learn about
        the training and education needed, costs, job prospects, salary, job
        duties, and advancement. With permission of your parent or guardian,
        your research methods may include an internet or library search, an
        interview with a professional in the field, or a visit to a location
        where people in this career work or train. Discuss your findings and
        career interest with your counselor. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/0M-WdfQlk3Q" target="_blank"
          >How I Got That Job: Public Radio (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/ftGPn35lNhw" target="_blank"
          >Broadcast Announcers and Radio Disc Jockeys Careers (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15558 mb-requirement-id-15560">
        (b) Explore how you could use radio knowledge and skills to develop a
        hobby or to serve as a volunteer. If possible, with permission of your
        parent or guardian, interview a radio hobbyist or volunteer. Research
        training and licensing needed, expenses, and organizations that promote
        or support your objectives. Discuss with your counselor what short-term
        and long-term goals you might have if you pursue this. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/sULPHxTkDnk" target="_blank"
          >(Hobbies) Ham Radio (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/sEDg7HycNU0" target="_blank"
          >5 MOST POPULAR Ham Radio Hobbies (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
</div>
